        <div class="browse">
            
            <div class="lesson boxed">
                <div class="title">
                    <h2>Display Tech: LCD vs. Plasma</h2>

                     <div class="lesson_meta">
                         <div class="byline">
                             <a rel="author" href="/tommypenner"><img src="http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/108/108927_30.jpg" alt="Tommy Penner" class="portrait portrait_sm" /></a>
                             by <a href="/tommypenner">Tommy Penner</a> <a tabindex="-1" href="/about" title="Learn more about Vimeo" data-ga-event-click="button|staff_badge_click|staff"><span class="badge_staff">Staff</span></a> <time datetime="2012-11-20T14:21:41-05:00" title="Tuesday, November 20, 2012 2:21 PM">Nov 20, 2012</time>                         </div>
                     </div>
                 </div>

                 <div class="content">
                    <p class="first">The weekend has arrived for you, fine filmmaker, and you're at the local electronics store buying all the necessary cables and adaptors needed to connect your computer to a TV. All of a sudden, you realize something: you don't even have a TV at home! How silly it would feel to make it back home with <a href="https://vimeo.com/videoschool/lesson/274/tvcomputer-connection-guide">these cables</a>, with no TV to connect them to! Luckily with all those <a href="https://vimeo.com/49684456">Tip Jar</a> tips, you feel comfortable enough to spend a few extra greenbacks on a brand-spanking-new TV. But the TV store is scary, with all these features and marketing terms competing for your attention. What the heck should I be looking for?</p>
<p>Before you make any decision on what TV you should purchase, it's good to know the essentials behind these big technological monoliths. There are several different types of display technologies out in the wild, but like America's political system nowadays, the TV space is mostly divided into two camps: <b>Plasma</b> and <b>LCD</b>.</p>
<p>Plasma screens are comprised of hundreds of thousands of tiny gas-filled cells sandwiched between two sheets of glass. When an electric charge is applied to one of these gas-filled cells it emits light, making up one of the thousands of pixels on-screen. </p>
<p><img src="http://a.vimeocdn.com/si/videoschool/tv-series-plasma-exploded.png" alt="" /><br>
A detailed exploded-view of a Plasma screen, courtesy of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plasma_screen" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>. <!-- more --></p>
<p>Generally, when compared with LCDs, Plasmas have the best <b>Contrast Ratio</b>, which means richer and more saturated color, and deep inky blacks. Additionally, Plasmas tend to have a better <b>viewing angle</b>, so if you have a large living room with friends sitting far off-center from the screen, they can still enjoy and experience the picture. If you're watching anything with fast motion, such as American football or hockey, you'll notice slightly less <b>motion blur</b> from Plasmas than LCD screens. </p>
<p>These advantages do come with a price. Plasma screens create more heat, so unless you also want a space heater for your apartment, this may be a concern. In addition to more heat, more electricity is required, making them slightly less eco-friendly. Plasmas are also thicker and heavier than their LCD cousins, so make sure you have a nice sturdy TV stand or an appropriate wall bracket. </p>
<p><b>LCD</b> screens, short for <b>Liquid Crystal Displays</b>, are similar to Plasmas in that a thin layer of special liquid-crystals lie between sheets of polarized glass or plastic. Each crystal forms one pixel on screen. An electric charge is applied to this liquid crystal, with the amount of electrical charge varying depending on the image being made. However, unlike a Plasma screen, the liquid crystals don't emit light, so a <b>backlight</b> lies behind the liquid crystal sandwich to illuminate the image. There are different types of backlighting that can affect image quality, which we'll cover below.</p>
<p><img src="http://a.vimeocdn.com/si/videoschool/tv-series-lcd-exploded.png" alt="" /><br>
A simplified diagram of the layers within an LCD screen. Image by <a href="https://vimeo.com/mattschwarz">Matt Schwarz</a>.</p>
<p>Since each pixel on an LCD screen isn't self-illuminating, LCDs consume less power and tend to generate less heat. If you're concerned about aesthetics, LCDs are also thinner and lighter than Plasmas. In terms of image quality, Plasmas still have a better contrast ratio, but LCDs are brighter and are easier to see in bright, sun-filled rooms.</p>
<p>The type of backlighting an LCD uses can dramatically affect the image quality on your screen. Many LCD screens today use <b>LED backlighting</b>. These sets may also be called <b>LED TVs</b>, so don't get confused! Older LCDs, and some current inexpensive LCDs, used CCFL (cold cathode fluorescent lamp) backlights. Since the CCFL can only be turned on or off, black pictures can appear more of a glowing dark gray color. </p>
<p>Unlike CCFL backlights, LED backlights can be controlled and dimmed, creating an image with contrast ratios as high as Plasma screens. These LCD TVs with <b>local dimming</b> LED backlighting are expensive, but can have very vivid colors and sharp details. Most LED-backlit screens are <b>edge-lit</b>, which makes for some of the thinnest TVs on the market today.</p>
<p>With all these details in mind, what should you pick when TV shopping? Consider the room where the screen is going, and what content you'll be watching the most. If your TV is going into a bright sunny living room, an LCD screen is your best bet. But if your TV is going into a dark room and you're intending to use it for <a href="https://vimeo.com/movies">Movies</a>, a Plasma screen may be better. Your best bet is to go to a store and lay your eyes on these screens side-by-side.</p>                </div>

                <dl class="context">
                    <dt class="category">Category:</dt>
                                                                    <dd><a href="/videoschool/archive/gear">Gear</a></dd>
                                        <dt class="difficulty">Difficulty:</dt>
                    <dd><a href="/videoschool/lessons/beginner">Beginner</a></dd>
                </dl>
            </div>

