<a href="/user14861647">
            <img src="http://b.vimeocdn.com/ps/456/300/4563007_75.jpg" alt="Jesse Goff" class="portrait portrait_lg">
    </a>

<div class="comment">
    <p class="meta">
        <a href="/user14861647" class="meta">Jesse Goff</a>  <time datetime="2012-11-24T09:02:59-05:00" title="Saturday, November 24, 2012 9:02 AM" pubdate>2 months ago</time>
            </p>

    
    <div class="text">
                <p class="first">We looked at many options years ago for our production studio and ended up buying two 50&quot; Panasonic commercial plasmas with BNC inputs and we bought the expansion card for a digital input.  Back then they were close to $5k each.  The motion picture quality is very good and the image quality still looks fine after 6 or 7 years of heavy use.  I find plasmas to have a more cinematic look to compared to LCDs.  But I also think the general public is generally clueless.  I walked into Best Buy the other day and saw all the latest and greatest sets with &quot;high refresh rates&quot;.  Everyone, including the staff at &quot;Magnolia&quot; thought they looked amazing.  I thought the refresh rate made a perfectly good 24p 35mm film look like a cartoon- fake and stroboscopic.  A step backwards.  The more the image quality looks natural as though your natural eye would see it, the better it is.  I monitor is like a fine men&#039;s suit- it should look really good, but nothing should stand out and distract you.</p>    </div>

    </div>

    </article>
